N2  - Welcome to the first issue of World Water Policy Journal for 2025. In this issue, we bring you another 21 contributions from around the world, including 1 guest editorial, 16 research articles, and 4 discussion papers. In practically all regions of the world, we can witness efforts to overcome complex challenges deriving from intersectional issues. Water is not independent of land use, environmental protection, urban development, agriculture, forestry, industrial uses, energy production, and other dimensions. Water is also not a unique and compartmentalized area of government. As we already stated, a couple of years ago, all challenges are interconnected, but our ability to predict, deal with, and adapt to the impact of those changes is not equal to all countries (Camkin and Neto 2022). Neither are the resources to minimize the impacts of climate change, conflict and wars, or migration issues. The world is facing many unbalancing factors that also have consequences for water security. Hegemonic uses of water resources cause unjust suffering and unequal life conditions in many communities. Related to water security, basic human rights to water were discussed at the UN Water Conference in Mar del Plata (1977), followed at the UN Conference on Environment and Development in Rio (1992), and formally recognized by the UN in 2002 as "the right to water as the right of everyone to sufficient, safe, acceptable and physically accessible and affordable water for personal and domestic uses" (Neto and Camkin 2024). In this unstable world where security threats are increasingly serious, the availability and sustainable management of water and sanitation for all must be ensured for global prosperity and peace (UN 2024). We trust the world will pursue this path of developing better approaches to water policy and water governance. If the lessons of some regions can be heard by others, at least we can keep learning and evolving towards more sustainability. In their guest editorial, Research on the Greening of Water Policy Needs to Move Beyond Supply and Demand-Oriented Logics to Achieve Water Sustainability for All, Franck Poupeau and Brian F. O'Neill reflect on the 10th Water Forum in 2024, recent research and current trends to unpack how supply and demand logics continue to inform policy dominated by "rational" economics. The authors argue that this has not led to the social structural transformations needed around the world, but rather to the re-emphasis of civil engineering exemplified by the rise of new mega-dams, desalination plants and other "new water" initiatives. Drawing lessons from examples including the US (Arizona), France (Paris), and Bolivia (El Alto), where a more precautionary approach was taken, they consider it necessary to rethink public and democratic action to ensure water is distributed in a more widely acceptable, equitable, and less destructive way by reducing the influence of abusive economic forces. The authors conclude that the 10th Water Forum did not seem to pay sufficient attention to the greening of water policy through ecological infrastructure. Building on a theme from our guest editorial, Sandra Megens and Jeroen Warner discuss the recent surge of scholarly interest in exploring the emergence of new governance regimes that redefine the self-governing capacities of local communities in water management while ensuring compliance with central government water laws and regulations in Invisible Threads: Emerging Water Governance in the Multi-Actor Dynamics of the Mira-Mataje Transboundary River Basin. Embracing polycentric governance emphasizes the importance of decentralized, collaborative systems for effectively and sustainably managing water resources. Focusing on actors' interactions around the downstream area of the Mira River basin, which is shared between Columbia and Ecuador, the authors employed a mixed-method approach to gain comprehensive insights into the complex interactions shaping transboundary water governance and community responses. Philamer Torio and Leila Harris focus on the significant role of tariffs for water services to not only achieve operational sustainability and efficiency goals but to also address the requirements of affordability and equity in Water Tariffs and Social Equity: Towards Water Service Connections and Pricing Instruments for the Poor. Noting that even with a well-designed water tariff, the inability of poor households to get piped connections results in the payment of premiums for water that is difficult to access and at times of questionable quality, the authors assess pro-poor projects of three municipal water systems in the Philippines, concluding that to ensure both operational viability and equitable water provision, designing tariffs for socioeconomic, political, and environmental realities must go hand-in-hand with programs that provide water service connections to poor households. In Autonomy Within Sovereignty: The Multi-Scalar Hydropolitics of the Kurdistan Regional Government, Rozita Meihami and co-authors examine the hydropolitical issues faced by the Kurdistan Regional Government within domestic and international contexts. The authors' historical review of the hydropolitics highlights the domestic and international dimensions of transboundary water politics and the power dynamics that underpin both water conflict and cooperation. Effective water management requires a holistic approach that integrates scientific understanding with active stakeholder participation. In Enhancing Participatory Planning for Water Management Through the Use of Innovative Tools in Collaborative Action Research, Chatthip Chaichakan and Dararat Khampeng present community-based water balance management (CBWBM) as a promising strategy to foster collaboration between communities and scientific experts. Drawing on case studies from rural Thailand, the authors report on their investigation into how innovative tools, grounded in futures studies and gamification approaches, can empower communities to actively participate in CBWBM planning processes, highlighting the importance of context-specific design and user-centered development to facilitate deliberative dialogue, knowledge exchange, and informed decision making. Following themes emerging in this issue, Jorge Cardoso-Gonçalves, José Tentúgal-Valente, and Diana Tavares discuss the importance of an integrated vision for water infrastructure management that includes the preservation of good basic practices, safeguarding of people and goods, valorization of water resources, promotion of efficient building solutions, and sustainability of public spaces in their paper Water Services. Circular Integrated Management as a management strategy. The authors present circular integrated management (CIM) as an integrated management strategy for water supply, wastewater, and rainwater drainage, considering the management of solid waste and urban space, as a common model, with the production of energy in water supply and water and wastewater treatment, and the recovery of treatment residues, also part of an integrated approach. Muhajir Mussa Kwikima's article, Enhancing Integrated Water Resources Management in Tanzania Through Participatory and Institutional Capacity Building Approaches, reports on an analysis of opportunities for advancing IWRM in Tanzania through participation and capacity-building interventions. Despite Tanzania's commitment to IWRM, the author identifies important capacity gaps, including hydrological monitoring, enforcement, and financial management, and makes several key recommendations to strengthen fragmented roles, address knowledge gaps, and empower stakeholders. Ensuring universal access to safe and affordable drinking water is a principal target of SDG 6. In Bridging Local Initiative and Global Goals: Role of Water Treatment Plant for Localizing Sustainable Development Goal 6, Target 6.1, Prasannata Lamichhane and co-authors present the results of their study on the role of the Dhulikhel Water Treatment Plant in Nepal in localizing SDG 6 at the municipal level. The authors discuss the complex dynamics of water tariffs and upstream-downstream conflicts and make recommendations for granular local-level measures to address potential contamination and improve equity of supply. In Investigating the Transforming Hydrosocial Dynamics in Urbanizing Gurgaon, India, Sheeba Amir and Vishal Narain reflect on the evolving interaction between water and society and the growing water insecurities within the "emerging" urban system of Gurgaon, a city peripheral to New Delhi. The authors discuss the transition of the area from a community-managed traditional water system to a centralized, extractive and techno-centric approach, along with the challenges, and vulnerabilities this has created. Understanding the negative impacts of land use/land cover (LULC) on water quality is key to developing effective integrated catchment management strategies. In Threats Posed by Land Use to Water Quality in South Africa's Strategic Water Source Areas, Kent Anson Locke and Kevin Winter discuss the application and implications of a recently published study on methods for estimating minimum thresholds of natural vegetation necessary for maintaining and protecting water quality in South African catchments. Focusing on the vulnerability of South Africa's strategic water source areas to land-use-related water quality impacts, the authors emphasize the need to restore and preserve sufficient areas of natural land cover to protect these strategic water resources. With the world population projected to grow to nearly 10 billion by 2050, increasing pressure on already scarce freshwater resources, J. Harsha discusses the idea of "saline water footprint" in Unlocking the Blue Frontier:Saline Water Footprint as a Path to Sustainability. Exploring the opportunities and limitations of increasing the use of saline water, the author recommends saline water footprint as an important contribution to integrated water management strategies. In Irrigation Project and Education: A Study on Teesta Barrage Irrigation Project Area of Nilphamari, Bangladesh, Md. Abu Shahen and Md. Nurul Momen present an investigation into how the Teesta Barrage Irrigation Project affects the education of farming families living in the project region. Finding that those in the middle and upper classes have benefited but lower levels have not, the authors make recommendations to address inconsistencies in water available for cultivation throughout the year. Reservoirs play a pivotal role in regulating the hydrological regime, with a range of benefits, but also have positive and negative impacts on the environment and societies. Important, but perhaps not widely recognized, is the impact construction of reservoirs has on soils. Drawing on examples from Ukraine, Maryna Ladyka and Ruofan Wu present their research on the physico-chemical properties of soils in The Impact of Reservoirs on the Soils of Adjacent Areas: Overview of Global and Local Aspects, advocating for the inclusion of these issues in a comprehensive approach to water resource management and environmental protection. Water quality assessment in freshwater ecosystems is crucial for understanding their health and ensuring safe water use for various domestic purposes. In Physicochemical characterization at the drawing and bathing points of Lake Kivu, by the Water Quality Index, Wand'arhasima L. finds that water quality at urban and rural drawing and bathing points is inadequate for sustaining aquatic life and that chemical treatment, disinfection, and rigorous monitoring are necessary for safe use. Concluding that physicochemical parameters are essential but not sufficient as a stand-alone analysis, the author proposes a multiparametric approach, including the World Health Organization cyanophycean standards for aquatic life and the health of beneficiaries/users. In Water Utilization Practices and Wastage at Household Level: A Case Study of Lahore City, Anam Chaudhry and co-authors present their research which found a clear correlation between water shortage and patterns of water utilization and waste. Noting that water shortages could hinder the sustainable development of the Punjab region in Pakistan, including Lahore, the authors propose a range of measures and household water-saving practices to better align water management with the SDG goals. Damte Tegegne Fetene, Tarun Kumar Lohani, and Abdella Kemal Mohammed report on their efforts to model the impact of climate change in Application of Coupled MIKE SHE/MIKE HYDRO on Streamflow Dynamics Under Climate Change in Lake Tana Sub Basin, Abay Basin, Ethiopia. In the case of Laka Tana Sub Basin, the study showed that conditions related to streamflow may change in the future due to climate alteration. The authors argue that by offering a better understanding of current and future climates, the integrated modeling system approach can assist environmentalists, hydrologists, and policymakers in water management and policy intervention. Watershed degradation is a significant global problem, but as a mountainous nation, Nepal faces even greater challenges in managing its water resources. In this context, sub-watershed prioritization is a promising approach for managing watersheds. In Prioritization of Sub-Watershed Using Remote Sensing and Geographical Information System in Gandaki Province, Nepal, Diwakar Poudel and co-authors delineated 121 sub-watersheds in the Gandaki Province and quantitatively ranked them to promote targeted action for water resource management, supporting ecosystem preservation, and climate resilience. Inappropriate use of chemical fertilizers and pesticides in rice farming can be a significant source of pollution in aquatic environments, resulting in declining water quality, impacts on aquatic life and health concerns for riparian communities. In Spatial Variation in Physico-Chemical Water Quality Parameters Associated with Rice Farming in the Dakalt Branch Canal, Kafrelsheikh Governorate, Egypt, Onyango Cersey Ochieng, Ogendi George Morara and Donia Noha Samir conclude from their study that poor rice management practices are responsible for pollution observed from the River Nile. The authors make recommendations for the monitoring of water quality and implementation of Best Management Practices in the application of pesticides and fertilizers. Agriculture plays a crucial role in ensuring food security and reducing poverty in Ethiopia, with rain-fed agriculture predominant. However, rainfall distribution and intensity vary spatially and temporally. Enhancing agricultural water management and irrigation has the potential to increase Ethiopia's agricultural productivity. In Assessment of Surface Irrigation Potential and Crop Water Demand in Daramalo Wereda, Southern Ethiopia, Ethiopia, Melkamu Ateka Derebe and Ligalem Agegn Asres evaluate surface water potential and the irrigation water demand of the Zage River sub-watershed. The findings that suggest the watershed has high surface water potential for surface irrigation for selected crop types are relevant to improving local water management policies and practices, enhancing agricultural productivity, and helping improve the food security of local farmers. In GIS Based Surface Irrigation Potential Assessment of Gololcha River Watershed, Awash Basin, Ethiopia, Wudad Yazid Abagissa and co-authors report on their evaluation of the potential land and water resources for surface irrigation in the watershed. While finding that only 14.15% of the total suitable land can be irrigated using existing flows, the authors note there is potential for expanding surface irrigation, particularly during the rainy seasons. These findings provide valuable insights for developing sustainable irrigation strategies, enhancing agricultural productivity, and contributing to food security in the region. In Hydrological Streamflow Modeling at the Inlet of Gilgel Gibe III Dam of Ethiopia using Soil and Water Assessment Tool, the final article in this issue, Yohannes Mehari Andiye and Tarun Kumar Lohani assessed the accuracy and applicability of the SWAT model in predicting streamflow at the inlet of the Gilgel Gibe III dam watershed. By demonstrating the model's effectiveness in simulating streamflow at the dam's inlet, the now calibrated and validated model can be used to study the effects of climate and land use changes, analyze water quality and sediment yield, and inform future water policy plans, dam construction planning, and flood disaster risk management. We trust you will enjoy reading another rich collection of insights into water policy, practice, and the learning that supports them from around the world. Thank you to all our authors for their fine contributions, to the dozens of reviewers who volunteered their time to support the authors and World Water Policy, and to our hard-working editorial team. The next issue of World Water Policy, to be published in May 2025, will be a special issue on Water Management Under Changing Climate: Innovative Approaches, Solutions, and Policies Towards Resilient Communities, featuring papers presented at Cairo Water Week 2024. Thank you for your ongoing interest in World Water Policy. We look forward to your contributions and other opportunities for collaboration in the future. Our best wishes Susana Neto and Jeff Camkin Editors-in-Chief 《世界水政策》新的一年 Susana Neto1,2* [email protected] and Jeff Camkin1 1Institute of Agriculture, University of Western Australia, Perth, Western Australia, Australia 2Civil Engineering Research and Innovation for Sustainability (CERIS), Instituto Superior Técnico, Universidade de Lisboa, Lisbon, Portugal 欢迎阅读2025年《世界水政策杂志》第一期。本期为您带来了来自世界各地的21篇文章, 包括一篇特约社论、16篇研究文章和4篇讨论文。 在世界几乎所有地区, 我们都能看到一系列用于克服"交叉问题的复杂挑战"的努力。水与土地使用、环境保护、城市发展、农业、林业、工业用途、能源生产和其他方面并不独立。水也不是独属于政府的单个领域。正如我们两年前所说的那样, 所有挑战都是相互关联的, 但各国在预测、处理和适应这些变化影响方面的能力并不相同(Camkin and Neto, 2022)。各国也没有相同的资源来尽量减少气候变化、冲突、战争或移民问题的影响。 世界正面临许多不平衡因素, 这些因素也会对水安全产生影响。对水资源的霸权使用导致许多社区遭受不公正的苦难和不平等的生活条件。与水安全相关的基本人权在马德普拉塔联合国水资源大会(1977)上进行了讨论, 随后又在里约联合国环境与发展大会(1992)上进行了讨论, 并于2002年被联合国正式承认为"享有水的权利意味着每个人都有权获得供个人和家庭使用的充足、安全、可接受、易于获取和负担得起的水"(Neto and Camkin, 2024)。 在这个安全威胁日益严重的不稳定世界中, 必须为所有人确保水和卫生设施的可用性和可持续管理, 以实现全球繁荣与和平(UN, 2024)。我们相信, 世界将制定更好的水政策和水治理方法。如果一些地区的经验教训能够被其他地区吸取, 至少我们能继续学习并朝着更可持续的方向发展。 在他们的特约社论《水政策绿化研究需要超越供需导向逻辑, 以期为全民实现水可持续性》中, Franck Poupeau和Brian F. O'Neill反思了2024年第10届水论坛、最新研究和当前趋势, 以揭示供需逻辑如何继续影响由"理性"经济学主导的政策。作者认为, 这并没有导致世界各地所需的社会结构转型, 而是重新强调了土木工程, 例如新建的大型水坝、海水淡化厂和其他"新水"计划的兴起。借鉴美国(亚利桑那州)、法国(巴黎)和玻利维亚(埃尔阿尔托)等采取更谨慎态度的例子, 他们认为有必要重新思考公共行动和民主行动, 以确保通过减少"滥用经济力量"的影响, 以更广泛接受、更公平、破坏性更小的方式分配水资源。作者总结称, 第十届水论坛似乎没有充分关注"通过生态基础设施"实现水政策绿化。 基于特约社论的主题, Sandra Megens和Jeroen Warner在《隐形的线索:米拉-马塔赫跨边界流域多行动者动态中的新兴水治理》一文中讨论了近期兴起的关于"探究新治理制度"的学术兴趣, 这些新治理制度重新定义了地方社区在水管理方面的自治能力, 同时确保遵守中央政府的水法律和监管。采用多中心治理一事强调了去中心化的协作系统对于"有效和可持续地管理水资源"一事的重要性。作者聚焦于哥伦比亚和厄瓜多尔共享的米拉河流域下游地区行动者的相互作用, 采用了一项混合方法, 以全面理解一系列影响跨边界水治理的复杂互动以及社区响应。 Philamer Torio和Leila Harris在《水价与社会公平:面向穷人的水服务连接与定价工具》一文中聚焦于水价在水服务中的重要作用, 它不仅有助于实现运营可持续性和效率目标, 还有助于满足可负担性和公平性要求。作者指出, 即使制定了完善的水价, 贫困家庭仍无法获得管道连接, 因此他们不得不为"难以获得且有时质量可疑的水"支付额外费用, 因此, 作者评估了菲律宾三个市政供水系统的扶贫项目, 并得出结论认为, 为确保运营可行性和公平供水, 设计符合社会-经济、政治和环境现实的水价必须与"为贫困家庭提供水服务连接"的计划齐头并进。 在《主权内的自治:库尔德斯坦地区政府的多尺度水政治》一文中, Rozita Meihami与合著者研究了库尔德斯坦地区政府在国内和国际情境下面临的水政治问题。作者对水政治的历史述评强调了跨边界水政治的国内和国际维度, 以及那些支撑水冲突与合作的权力动态。 有效的水管理需要一种将科学理解与利益攸关方的积极参与相结合的整体方法。在《通过在协同行动研究中使用创新工具来加强水管理的参与式规划》一文中, Chatthip Chaichakan和Dararat Khampeng提出, 以社区为基础的水平衡管理(CBWBM)是一种有前途的战略, 能促进社区与科学专家之间的合作。通过借鉴泰国农村的案例研究, 作者报告了他们的研究结果, 即基于未来研究和游戏化方法的创新工具如何能使社区能够积极参与CBWBM规划过程, 强调了针对具体情况的设计和以用户为中心的开发对"促进协商对话、知识交流和知情决策"一事的重要性。 与本期主题一致的是, Jorge Cardoso-Gonçalves、José Tentúgal-Valente和Diana Tavares在论文《水服务:循环综合管理作为一种管理策略》中讨论了水基础设施管理综合愿景的重要性, 其中包括维护良好的基本实践、保护人员和货物、水资源增值、促进高效的建筑解决方案、以及公共空间的可持续性。作者提出了循环综合管理(CIM)作为供水、废水和雨水排放的综合管理策略, 将固体废物和城市空间的管理视为一种共同模式, 供水和水及废水处理中的能量生产以及处理残留物的回收也是综合方法的一部分。 Muhajir Mussa Kwikima的文章《通过参与式和制度能力建设方法加强坦桑尼亚水资源综合管理》报告了一项分析, 即通过参与和能力建设干预措施来推进坦桑尼亚的水资源综合管理。尽管坦桑尼亚致力于水资源综合管理, 但作者指出了重要的能力差距, 包括水文监测、执法和财务管理, 并提出了几项关键建议, 以加强分散的角色, 解决知识差距并对利益攸关方赋权。 确保全民获得安全且负担得起的饮用水是可持续发展目标6的主要目标。在《连接地方倡议和全球目标:水处理厂在实现可持续发展目标6、具体目标6.1方面的作用》一文中, Prasannata Lamichhane与合著者介绍了他们关于"尼泊尔Dhulikhel水处理厂在市政层面实现可持续发展目标6方面的作用"的研究结果。作者探讨了水价和上下游冲突的复杂动态, 并就详细的当地措施提出了一系列建议, 用于应对潜在污染和改善供应公平性。 在《调查印度古尔冈城市化过程中不断变化的水社会动态》一文中, Sheeba Amir和Vishal Narain反思了水与社会之间不断发展的互动, 以及古尔冈(新德里周边城市之一)这一"新兴"城市系统中日益严重的水不安全问题。作者讨论了该地区从社区管理的传统供水系统向集中式、提取式和技术中心式方法的转变, 以及由此带来的挑战和脆弱性。 理解土地利用/土地覆盖(LULC)对水质的负面影响是制定有效的综合集水区管理战略的关键。在《土地利用对南非战略水源区水质构成的威胁》一文中, Kent Anson Locke和Kevin Winter讨论了最近发表的一项研究的应用和影响, 该研究聚焦于一系列用于估计"维持和保护南非集水区水质所需的自然植被最低阈值"的方法。作者重点关注南非战略水源区对土地利用相关水质影响的脆弱性, 强调需要恢复和保留足够面积的自然土地覆盖以保护这些战略水资源。 预计到2050年, 世界人口将增长至近100亿, 这将给本已稀缺的淡水资源带来更多压力。J Harsha在《解锁蓝色边界:盐水足迹作为可持续性道路》一文中讨论了"盐水足迹"的概念。作者探究了"增加盐水使用"一事的机会和局限性, 建议将盐水足迹作为综合水管理战略的一项重要贡献。 在《灌溉项目与教育:孟加拉国Nilphamari地区Teesta拦水坝灌溉项目区研究》一文中, Md. Abu Shahen和Md. Nurul Momen研究了Teesta拦河坝灌溉项目如何影响项目区农民家庭的教育。作者发现, 中上阶层受益, 但下层阶级没有受益, 因此提出了用于应对"全年耕作用水不一致"问题的建议。 水库在调节水文状况方面发挥着关键作用, 具有一系列益处, 但对环境和社会也有积极和消极的影响。水库建设对土壤的影响很重要, 但可能并未得到广泛认可。Maryna Ladyka和Ruofan Wu借鉴乌克兰的例子, 在《水库对邻近地区土壤的影响:全球和地方概况》一文中介绍了他们对土壤理化性质的研究, 倡导将这些问题纳入水资源管理和环境保护的综合方法中。 淡水生态系统的水质评估对于理解其健康状况和确保各种家庭用途的安全用水至关重要。在《通过水质指数描述基伍湖取水点和沐浴点的理化特性》一文中, Wand'arhasima L发现, 城市和农村取水点和沐浴点的水质不足以维持水生生物, 并且化学处理、消毒和严格监测对于安全用水是必要的。作者认为理化参数是必不可少的, 但作为独立分析还不够, 因此提出了一种多参数方法, 包括世界卫生组织针对水生生物和受益者/用户健康的蓝藻标准。 在《家庭用水实践与浪费:拉合尔市案例研究》一文中, Anam Chaudhry与合著者介绍了他们的研究, 该研究发现, 水资源短缺与水资源利用和浪费模式之间存在明显的相关性。作者指出, 水资源短缺可能会阻碍包括拉合尔在内的巴基斯坦旁遮普地区的可持续发展, 并提出了一系列措施和家庭节水做法, 以使水资源管理更好地与可持续发展目标保持一致。 Damte Tegegne Fetene、Tarun Kumar Lohani和Abdella Kemal Mohammed在《耦合MIKE SHE/MIKE HYDRO 应用于埃塞俄比亚阿拜盆地塔那湖子流域气候变化下的径流动态》一文中报告了他们为模拟气候变化影响所作的努力。在塔那湖子流域的案例中, 研究表明, 由于气候变化, 未来与径流相关的条件可能会发生变化。作者认为, 通过更好地理解当前和未来的气候, 综合建模系统方法能帮助环保主义者、水文学家和政策制定者进行水管理和政策干预。 流域退化是一个重大的全球性问题, 但尼泊尔作为一个山地国家, 在管理其水资源方面面临着更大的挑战。在此情境下, 子流域优先排序是一种有前途的流域管理方法。在《利用遥感和地理信息系统对尼泊尔甘达基省子流域进行优先排序》一文中, Diwakar Poudel与合著者在甘达基省划定了121个子流域, 并对其进行了量化排名, 以促进有针对性的水资源管理行动, 支持生态系统保护和气候适应能力。 水稻种植中化学肥料和农药的不当使用可能是水生环境污染的重要来源, 导致水质下降、水生生物受到影响以及沿岸社区的健康问题。在《埃及卡夫雷尔谢赫省Dakalt支渠水稻种植相关的理化水质参数的空间变化》一文中, Onyango Cersey Ochieng、Ogendi George Morara和Donia Noha Samir从他们的研究中得出结论, 即不良的水稻管理实践是尼罗河污染的原因。作者就水质监测和"农药和化肥施用方面的最佳管理实践"的实施提出了建议。 农业在确保埃塞俄比亚的粮食安全和减贫 方面发挥着至关重要的作用, 雨养农业在埃塞俄比亚占主导地位。然而, 降雨分布和强度在空间和时间上各不相同。加强农业用水管理和灌溉, 有可能提高埃塞俄比亚的农业生产力。在《埃塞俄比亚南部Daramalo Wereda地表灌溉潜力和作物需水量评估》一文中, Melkamu Ateka Derebe和Ligalem Agegn Asres评价了扎格河子流域的地表水潜力和灌溉需水量。研究结果表明, 该流域具有较高的地表水潜力, 可用于某些作物类型的地表灌溉, 这一研究结果对于改善当地水管理政策和实践、提高农业生产力、以及帮助改善当地农民的粮食安全一事至关重要。在《埃塞俄比亚阿瓦什盆地戈洛尔恰河流域基于GIS的地表灌溉潜力评估》一文中, Wudad Yazid Abagissa与合著者报告了他们对用于流域地表灌溉的潜在土地和水资源的评估。虽然作者发现, 只有14.15%的土地可通过现有水流加以灌溉, 但作者指出, 扩大地面灌溉一事具有潜力, 特别是在雨季。这些发现为制定可持续灌溉战略、提高农业生产力、以及促进该地区的粮食安全提供了宝贵的见解。在本期最后一篇文章《使用土壤和水评估工具对埃塞俄比亚Gilgel Gibe III大坝入口的水文径流进行建模》中, Yohannes Mehari Andiye和Tarun Kumar Lohani评估了SWAT模型在预测Gilgel Gibe III大坝流域入口径流方面的准确性和适用性。通过展示该模型在模拟大坝入口径流方面的有效性, 现已校准和验证的模型可用于研究气候和土地利用变化的影响, 分析水质和泥沙产量, 并为"未来的水政策计划、大坝建设规划和洪灾风险管理"提供信息。 我们相信您将享受阅读本期关于水政策、实践以及"世界各地用于支持这些政策与实践的学习"的丰富见解。感谢所有作者的出色稿件, 感谢数十位自愿抽出时间支持作者和《世界水政策》的审稿人, 以及我们辛勤工作的编辑团队。 《世界水政策》下一期将于2025年5月出版, 它将是一期特刊, 主题为"气候变化下的水管理:面向复原力社区的创新方法、解决方案与政策", 聚焦于2024年"开罗水周"上发表的论文。 感谢您对《世界水政策》的持续关注。我们期待您的投稿和其他合作机会。 献上最美好的祝愿 Susana Neto 和 Jeff Camkin 主编 关键词:水治理, 水政策, 可持续发展目标6, 水资源综合管理, 循环性与水服务, 水与粮食安全 参考文献 Camkin, J. and Neto, S. 2022. Climate Change May Connect Us, But Global Inequities Perpetuate Vastly Different Impacts. Editorial. World Water Policy Journal. Vol 8, Issue 2. 27 October 2022. Wiley. https://doi.org/10.1002/wwp2.12088 Neto, S. and Camkin, J. (2024). Water Diplomacy: More Than a Drop of Wisdom. Editorial. World Water Policy Journal. Vol 10, Issue 4. 28 November 2024. Wiley. https://doi.org/10.1002/wwp2.12237. United Nations 2024. UN World Water Development Report. Launched 19 March 2024. Accessible at https://www.unwater.org/publications/un-world-water-development-report-2024 Un nuevo año de World Water Policy Susana Neto1,2* [email protected] y Jeff Camkin1 1Institute of Agriculture, University of Western Australia, Perth, Western Australia, Australia 2Civil Engineering Research and Innovation for Sustainability (CERIS), Instituto Superior Técnico, Universidade de Lisboa, Lisboa, Portugal Bienvenidos al primer número de la Revista World Water Policy en 2025. En este número, les traemos otras 21 contribuciones de todo el mundo, incluido un editorial invitado, 16 artículos de investigación y 4 documentos de debate. En prácticamente todas las regiones del mundo podemos observar esfuerzos por superar desafíos complejos derivados de cuestiones interseccionales. El agua no es independiente del uso de la tierra, la protección del medio ambiente, el desarrollo urbano, la agricultura, la silvicultura, los usos industriales, la producción de energía y otras dimensiones. El agua tampoco es un área única y compartimentada de gobierno. Como ya dijimos hace un par de años, todos los desafíos están interconectados, pero nuestra capacidad para predecir, abordar y adaptarnos al impacto de esos cambios no es igual en todos los países (Camkin y Neto, 2022). Tampoco lo son los recursos para minimizar los impactos del cambio climático, los conflictos y las guerras, o las cuestiones migratorias. El mundo se enfrenta a numerosos factores desequilibrantes que también tienen consecuencias para la seguridad hídrica. Los usos hegemónicos de los recursos hídricos provocan sufrimiento injusto y condiciones de vida desiguales en muchas comunidades. En relación con la seguridad hídrica, los derechos humanos básicos al agua se debatieron en la Conferencia de las Naciones Unidas sobre el Agua en Mar del Plata (1977), siguieron en la Conferencia de las Naciones Unidas sobre el Medio Ambiente y el Desarrollo en Río (1992) y fueron reconocidos formalmente por las Naciones Unidas en 2002 como "el derecho al agua como el derecho de toda persona a agua suficiente, salubre, aceptable, físicamente accesible y asequible para uso personal y doméstico" (Neto y Camkin, 2024). En este mundo inestable donde las amenazas a la seguridad son cada vez más graves, es necesario garantizar la disponibilidad y la gestión sostenible del agua y el saneamiento para todos, en aras de la prosperidad y la paz mundiales (ONU, 2024). Confiamos en que el mundo seguirá este camino para desarrollar mejores enfoques en materia de políticas y gobernanza del agua. Si las lecciones de algunas regiones pueden ser escuchadas por otras, al menos podremos seguir aprendiendo y evolucionando hacia una mayor sostenibilidad. En su editorial invitada, La investigación sobre la ecologización de las políticas hídricas debe ir más allá de las lógicas orientadas a la oferta y la demanda para lograr la sostenibilidad del agua, Franck Poupeau y Brian F. O'Neill reflexionan sobre el 10º Foro del Agua en 2024, las investigaciones recientes y las tendencias actuales para desentrañar cómo las lógicas de oferta y demanda siguen informando las políticas dominadas por la economía "racional". Los autores sostienen que esto no ha llevado a las transformaciones estructurales sociales necesarias en todo el mundo, sino más bien a un nuevo énfasis en la ingeniería civil ejemplificado por el surgimiento de nuevas megapresas, plantas de desalinización y otras iniciativas de "nueva agua". Extrayendo lecciones de ejemplos como los de Estados Unidos (Arizona), Francia (París) y Bolivia (El Alto), donde se adoptó un enfoque más precautorio, consideran que es necesario repensar la acción pública y democrática para garantizar que el agua se distribuya de una manera más ampliamente aceptable, equitativa y menos destructiva, reduciendo la influencia de fuerzas económicas abusivas. Los autores concluyen que el X Foro del Agua no parece haber prestado suficiente atención a la ecologización de la política hídrica a través de la infraestructura ecológica. Basándose en un tema de nuestro editorial invitado, Sandra Megens y Jeroen Warner discuten el reciente aumento del interés académico en explorar el surgimiento de nuevos regímenes de gobernanza que redefinen las capacidades de autogobierno de las comunidades locales en la gestión del agua, al tiempo que garantizan el cumplimiento de las leyes y regulaciones del agua del gobierno central en Hilos invisibles: gobernanza emergente del agua en la dinámica multiactor de la cuenca transfronteriza del río Mira-Mataje. La adopción de una gobernanza policéntrica enfatiza la importancia de los sistemas descentralizados y colaborativos para gestionar de manera eficaz y sostenible los recursos hídricos. Centrándose en las interacciones de los actores en torno al área de aguas abajo de la cuenca del río Mira, que comparten Colombia y Ecuador, los autores emplearon un enfoque de métodos mixtos para obtener conocimientos integrales sobre las interacciones complejas que dan forma a la gobernanza del agua transfronteriza y las respuestas de la comunidad. Philamer Torio y Leila Harris se centran en el importante papel de las tarifas de los servicios de agua, no sólo para alcanzar objetivos de sostenibilidad y eficiencia operativa, sino también para abordar los requisitos de asequibilidad y equidad en Tarifas de agua y equidad social: hacia conexiones de servicios de agua e instrumentos de fijación de precios para los pobres. Observando que incluso con una tarifa de agua bien diseñada, la incapacidad de los hogares pobres para obtener conexiones por tuberías da lugar al pago de primas por agua a la que es difícil acceder y, a veces, de calidad cuestionable, los autores evalúan proyectos en favor de los pobres de tres sistemas de agua municipales en Filipinas, y concluyen que, para garantizar tanto la viabilidad operativa como el suministro equitativo de agua, el diseño de tarifas para las realidades socioeconómicas, políticas y ambientales debe ir de la mano con programas que proporcionen conexiones de servicios de agua a los hogares pobres. En Autonomía dentro de la soberaní
