N2  - JBI Centre College of Public Health and Medical Sciences, Jimma University Ethiopia - JBI Centre for Evidence Synthesis P. O. Box- 378 Jimma, Ethiopia Collaborating Institution: Joanna Briggs Institute, Faculty of Health Sciences, The University of Adelaide, South Australia, SA 5005, Australia Review Questions/ Objectives What is the effect of Schistosoma infection on malaria immune response in above 4 year old individuals and what implications does this have on malaria vaccine trials in sub- Saharan Africa? Objective The objective of this review is to systematically search, appraise and synthesize the best available evidence on the effect of Schistosoma infection on the immune response to Malaria antigens and provide direction to future Malaria vaccination trials. Background Worldwide an estimated number of 225 million cases and about 800, 000 deaths occurred due to Malaria in the year 2009 1. Malaria is caused by a protozoan parasite plasmodium2. Four species of the plasmodium genus cause malaria in humans: P. falciparum, P. vivax, P. ovale, and P. malariae.3 Currently, there are several malaria control strategies such as residual house spraying, insecticide-treated bed nets, and anti-malarial drugs. Due to drug resistance of the parasites, chemical resistance of the vectors, and given the time and cost required for the development of new anti-malarial drugs, malaria vaccines have been developed as a future malaria control strategy. 4, 5 Several antigens of the plasmodium species have been developed for use as a malaria vaccine. These antigens are classified as pre-erythrocytic vaccines, erythrocytic vaccines, and transmission blocking vaccines. Hereafter we will refer to malaria vaccines that have entered into clinical trials. Pre-erythrocytic vaccines includes circumsporozoite protein vaccines (RTS,S, CS102, and MAP), and DNA vaccines (Plasmid DNA vaccines such as the Multi-Stage DNA Operation, MuStDO; and Live Recombinant Vaccines that use the attenuated modified vaccinia Ankara (MVA), fowlpoxvirus (FPV), Adenovirus, Sindbis virus, yellow fever virus or a cold adapted influenza virus strain as a vector. 6-11 Erythrocytic vaccines consists of SPf66 vaccine, merozoite surface proteins 1 (MSP-1), 2 (MSP-2), 3 (MSP-3), the apical membrane antigen-1 (AMA-1) and the glutamate-rich protein (GLURP). 12, 13 Transmission-blocking vaccines include vaccines that contain the P. falciparum ookinate surface antigens Pfs25 and Pfs28 as well as their P. vivax homologues Pvs25 and Pvs28.14-16 Among the malaria vaccines erythrocytic malaria vaccines such as MSP are the most advanced. 17 These malaria vaccines require a coordinated humeral and cell-mediated immune response to offer immunity to malaria. The humeral immunity is affected by merozoite specific IgG1, IgG2, and IgG3 antibody responses that block merozoite invasion of Red Blood Cells (RBCs) and is also the main mechanism of immune response. 18 In addition to antibody response an immune response mediated by CD4+ T cell and B-cell, which occurs after infection is required for a full protection. 19, 20 A high antibody response, 21, 22 persistence of memory B cells to the MSP 23 and lack of apoptotic deletion of parasite specific Th1 CD4+ T cells 24 are required for long-term immunity after malaria vaccination. Moreover, pro-inflammatory cytokines such as IFN-γ, IL-10 and TGF-β play a role in malaria immunity. Anti-IFN-γ treatment prevents apoptosis of Th1 CD4+ T cells, 24 implicating IFN-γ as an inhibitory factor to the long-term immunity. TGF- β is also known to inhibit Th2 CD4+ T cells. 25 While IL-10 protect against severe Th1 mediated pathogenesis in Plasmodium berghei infections. 26 Thus, long-term immunity to malaria could be affected by any factor that could affect the humeral, cell-mediated, and pro-inflammatory cytokine immune responses described above. One of these factors is co-infection of a patient with both malaria and other diseases. Recent studies have shown an inverse relationship between CD+ T cells number and plasmodium parasite density in individuals co-infected with Human Immune Deficiency Virus (HIV) and malaria. 27 Helminthes which are chronic parasitic infections also affect long-term immune response to malaria by biasing the immune response from Th1 to Th2 response and leading to cellular hypo-responsiveness. 28 Schistosomes which belong to the blood flukes trematode genus Schistosoma consists of five species which cause human schistosomiasis: the intestinal species S. mansoni, S. japonicum, S. mekongi, and S. intercalatum and the urinary species S. haematobium.29, 30 Among these species S.mansoni, S. hematobium, and S.intercalatum are common in Africa. 31 Schistosomiasis has been shown to infect approximately 200 million people around the world, 80 % of which live in sub-Saharan Africa. 32 Most of the people infected by schistosomiasis are school-age children exposed to river water harbouring the intermediate snail for Schistosoma. 33 Due to their limited mobility, the prevalence of schistosomiasis in children under five years of age is very low to 0%. 34 Malaria and Schistosomiasis are often geographically co-endemic in sub-Saharan Africa. 35 Co-infections may affect the level of morbidity and immunological factors may alter responses to common treatment options. 36, 37Schistosoma mansoni has reduced the incidence of cerebral malaria in mice infected with S. mansoni and co-infected with Plasmodium berghei 7 weeks after by biasing the immune response towards Th2. 38 In addition, children lightly infected with Schistosoma hematobium were found to have low plasmodium parasite densities than those who were not infected. 39 Therefore, due to its co-endemicity and wider geographic area it shares with malaria as well as its effect on malaria immune response, schistosomiasis should be considered as a confounding factor in any study that aims to measure immune response after a challenge with a candidate malaria vaccine. Thus, the evidence on the effect of Schistosoma infection on malaria immune response needs to be synthesized so that future malaria vaccination trials as well as mass Schistosoma treatment campaigns would affect into account as a confounding factor. The presence of existing systematic reviews on the current topic was assessed with a thorough search of major databases including: Mednar, Pubmed, EMBASE, JBI Library of Systematic Reviews, Cochrane Library of Systematic Reviews, and CINAHL. The search revealed an absence of systematic reviews with a similar question and objectives. However, few primary observational studies are available: a cross-sectional pilot study from Ghana,40 and cohort studies from Senegal and Mali. 41-43 To date there are no systematic reviews which have examined the effect of Schistosoma infection on malaria immune response. Therefore, this review will provide the best available evidence for the effects of Schistosoma infection on Malaria immune response in co-infected individuals. Since this review is about the relationship between Schistosoma infection and immune response to malaria observational studies such as cross-sectional, case-control, and cohort studies will be used. Inclusion criteria Types of Studies This review will consider: Cross-sectional, Cohort, Case-control studies, Randomised Controlled Trials and Quasi-Randomised Controlled Trial will be included. Types of Participants- This review will consider studies where the subjects included are above 4 years old individuals and have diagnoses of Schistosoma and Malaria as an intervention group; and a diagnosis of malaria only as a control group. Phenomenon of interest The phenomenon of interest if the presence of Schistosoma infection and immune response to Malaria Comparator The review will consider studies where the control subjects are individuals infected with Malaria and without Schistosoma infection. Types of Outcomes The outcomes of interest for this review are measures of immune response to Malaria in individuals infected with Schistosoma species. Anticipated outcome measures include: Primary outcome: will be expressed in the form of the number of persons with a plasmodium specific Th1 (protect against liver stage parasites) and Th2 (protect against blood stage parasites) immune response to MSPs 1, 2, and 3 of Plasmodium species. Secondary Outcome: will be expressed in the form of the number of persons with plasmodium specific Immune response in the form of IgG 1, IgG 2, IgG3,INF-γ, IL-10, and TGF-β Exclusion criteria Case series or case reports will be excluded from the analysis, because they are not strong enough to show the relationship between Schistosoma infection and malaria immune response. Studies on less than 4 years old individuals will also be excluded from the review. Additionally, studies on the relationship between Malaria immune response and helminthes other that Schistosomiasis, HIV co-infected individuals, and pregnant women will be excluded from the analysis. Studies with control subjects with Malaria and co-infection with other parasites will also be excluded. Search strategy This review will consider studies conducted after 1994 (time the term Malaria vaccine is introduced), to the present date. The search strategy will focus on Population, Intervention, Comparator, and Outcomes and will be breakdown into specific search terms.Table 1: Overview of search termsThe search strategy aims to find both published and unpublished studies. A three-step search strategy will be utilized. An initial limited search of Medline and CINAHL will be undertaken followed by analysis of the text words contained in the title and abstract, and of the index terms used to describe the article. A second search using all of the identified keywords and index terms will be undertaken across all of the included databases. Thirdly, the reference lists of all identified reports and articles will be search for additional studies. The initial search terms are listed below and will be modified for the various databases and search engines. ["Child" OR "Children"] AND ["age 5-14 years"] AND ["malaria and Schistosoma co-infection"] AND ["Schistosoma infection" OR "s.hematobium" OR "s. mansoni"] AND "[plasmodium falciparum" OR "plasmodium vivax" infection] AND ["Th1" OR "Th2" OR "IgG1" OR "IgG2" OR "IgG3"OR "IFN-γ" OR "IL-10" OR "TGF-β"] Databases to be searched include: PubMed, CINAHL, EMBASE, Mednar, Proquest, and Hinari. Assessment of Methodological quality: The papers selected for retrieval will be assessed by two independent reviewers for methodological validity prior to inclusion in the review using standardized critical appraisal instruments from the Joanna Briggs Institute Meta Analysis of Statistics Assessment and Review Instrument (JBI-MAStARI). Each paper will be critically appraised by two independent reviewers using the JBI-MASTARI Critical Appraisal Instrument (Appendix I) and any disagreement that arise between reviewers will be resolved through discussion or by consultation with a third reviewer. Extraction of data Data will be extracted from studies that fulfil the inclusion criteria using a standardized data extraction tool from JBI- MASTARI (Appendix - II). The data extracted will include details about the phenomenon of interest, population, study methods and outcomes of significance to the review question and review objectives. Data Analysis/Data Synthesis Quantitative papers will, were possible will be pooled in statistical meta-analysis using JBI-MAStARI. All results will be subject to double data entry. Where statistical pooling is not appropriate or possible, the findings will be presented in narrative summary. Conflict of Interest Neither financial nor intellectual conflicts of interest are associated with this work with other organizations or individuals. Acknowledgments We would like to acknowledge the JBI -Jimma University Collaborating Centre for providing the training on conducting systematic reviews.
