N2  - The steady decline in global malaria burden between 2000 and 2015 averted millions of deaths via diagnosis, treatment, and vector control, but disturbingly stagnated between 2016 and 2017, as shown in the WHO World Malaria Report 2018,1WHOWorld malaria report 2018. World Health Organization, Geneva2018https://www.who.int/malaria/publications/world-malaria-report-2018/en/Date accessed: March 2, 2019Google Scholar which signals a wake-up call for response. By 2017, approximately 70% of the 219 million malaria cases were ascribed to ten African countries and India. The report also revealed an estimated additional 3·5 million cases in 2017 compared with 2016 in sub-Saharan Africa, with only 50% coverage of effective vector control in this region.1WHOWorld malaria report 2018. World Health Organization, Geneva2018https://www.who.int/malaria/publications/world-malaria-report-2018/en/Date accessed: March 2, 2019Google Scholar Notably, the suboptimal coverage and the inherent need to strengthen vector control cannot be over-emphasised. Efforts have been galvanised in the context of integrated vector management through the WHO Global Technical Strategy for Malaria 2016–30 and the Global Vector Control Response 2017–30 with an ultimate goal of implementing effective, locally adaptive, and sustainable vector control.2Chanda E Measuring the effect of insecticide resistance: are we making progress?.Lancet Infect Dis. 2018; 18: 586-588Summary Full Text Full Text PDF PubMed Scopus (4) Google Scholar Regrettably, contemporary vector control efforts are characterised by various challenges such as insecticide resistance, epidemics and emergencies, and residual transmission.3WHOGuidelines for malaria vector control. World Health Organization, Geneva2019https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/310862/9789241550499-eng.pdf?ua=1Date accessed: March 2, 2019Google Scholar Mitigation measures include resistance management strategies (ie, larval source management) and use of in