N2  - The current need to produce marketable vegetables entails increasing pressure to use agricultural pesticides. However, information on the type of pesticide residues, the concentration in the soil, and their prolonged impacts is lacking in developing countries such as Ethiopia. Therefore, the present work was conducted to identify the types of pesticide residues and measure their concentration in the soil. Surface soil samples were collected from vegetable‐growing farmlands. The types of pesticide residues and their concentrations in the samples were analyzed using LC‐MS/MS triple quadrant with an ESI ion source. The physicochemical properties of the soils were also determined following appropriate procedures. The analytical method was accurate with a percentage recovery of 71%–120% and acceptable with correlation coefficients greater than 0.992. The detection limits and quantifications were within the range of 0.3–1 and 1–3.3 μg/kg, respectively. A total of ten different pesticide residues were found, of which diazinon, dimethoate, malathion, metalaxyl, and profenofos were found in all samples. Profenofos and metalaxyl were the pesticide residues found at high concentrations (116.16 and 106.03 μg/kg, respectively). The textural classes of the samples were clay‐loam with high acidity, which might be associated with the intensive application of pesticides. The results revealed that different pesticide residues were present in the soil, some of which are persistent and hazardous to health and the environment. Authorities must take appropriate measures to reduce the impact on health and ensure sustainable soil productivity in the area.
