N2  - Food security is paramount for developing nations grappling with chal-lenges like population growth, limited arable land, and climate change. To tackle these issues, fostering innovation in agriculture and environmental sustainability is crucial. In the developing world, environmental degradation primarily stems from deforestation, land degradation, and water scarcity that harm agriculture by dimin-ishing biodiversity, essential for soil fertility and pollination. Furthermore, land degradation reduces available cultivable land, posing a substantial obstacle to agricul-tural production in many developing nations. Climate change-induced water scarcity hinders agriculture in developing nations. Agrarian innovation, such as sustain-able intensification, utilizes advanced technology to increase productivity while minimizing environmental impact. Precision agriculture optimizes yields, conserves resources, and reduces environmental harm. Conservation agriculture, employing practices like crop rotation and cover cropping, preserves soil fertility and reduces input dependency, like fertilizers and pesticides, exemplifying innovative agricultural approaches. Achieving food security in developing nations necessitates both agri-cultural and environmental sustainability innovation. This entails adopting renew-able energy sources such as solar and wind power to reduce fossil fuel dependence and greenhouse gas emissions. Agroforestry, involving tree planting on agricul-tural land, enhances soil fertility, carbon sequestration, and environmental bene-fits, showcasing sustainability innovation. Numerous case studies underscore the importance of environmental and agricultural innovation in enhancing food security in developing nations. The Green Revolution in India, utilizing high-yield crops, fertilizers, and irrigation, significantly boosted agricultural output. Precision agri-culture in India increased yields while conserving resources. Conservation agri-culture improved output and reduced input demand in Africa, as seen in Zambia. Agroforestry in Ethiopia enhanced soil fertility and climate resilience for farmers. Environmental degradation and limited arable land hinder agricultural output in many emerging nations, necessitating inventive solutions for food security. Preci-sion, conservation, and sustainable intensification represent agricultural innovations, while agroforestry and renewable energy sources signify environmental sustain-ability innovations. India and Africa’s case studies highlight how innovation can enhance agricultural productivity and address global food security challenges. © The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2024.
