N2  - Khat, a leafy bush whose leaves are chewed for a mild amphetamine effect, has been chewed in Ethiopia, Yemen, and Kenya for centuries in ritual and social contexts. In the last century, khat chewing has become more widespread in Africa as well as in the global north following the diaspora from Yemen and the Horn of Africa. In places where it is grown (primarily Kenya, Ethiopia, and Yemen, but also in Madagascar), it is the life's blood of local economies and, in some places, critical to the national economy, despite uneven legal status and sometimes strong public condemnation of the substance. This chapter provides an overview of the effects of khat on environment and health in the countries where it is produced and consumed, including original research conducted in Madagascar, where it was introduced during the French colonial era by dock workers from Yemen in the early twentieth century. The chapter argues that Khat has had mixed effects. On the one hand, khat production is linked to overuse of water, negative health effects of pesticides, and the supply of a substance whose purchase poor households can ill-afford. On the other hand, khat provides a significant income for farmers and traders. The chapter takes political ecology of health approach, which evaluates consumption, distribution, and production in the context of the broader political, economic, environmental, and health concerns.
