N2  - This chapter examines the outcomes of weed management research and development in Ethiopia and identifies future priority areas. So far, nearly 1100 weed species representing 552 genera and 126 plant families have been registered. Weeds in this country can cause a minimum of ~15% to a total crop failure. The research system has accomplished several milestones, including evaluation of new herbicides and development of herbicide recom¬mendations, non-chemical methods (including weed biology and dynamics in crops and cropping systems), management of regular, parasitic and invasive species, and transfer of management technologies. There have also been successes in the biological control of the whitetop weed (Parthenium hysterophorus) and integrated management of the witchweed (Striga hermonthica) on sorghum, and management of herbicide-resistant annual and perennial grasses. Future emphasis will include risk analysis, invasive alien and parasitic weeds, biocontrol, herbicide resistance, herbicide-tolerant crops, herbicide residue and environmental safety. © CAB International 2024. All rights reserved.
